{"key":"processedPost-8730883","value":{"id":8730883,"first":8721250,"last":8731422,"when":1217987927,"utime":"08/06/08 04:58 AM","content":"One of the biggest causes of bacterial contamination is the exhaled breath of the cultivator, and to a lesser degree, bacteria from under the fingernails and other skin cells that shed during the process.&nbsp; That's why it's important to use a glovebox or flowhood, and as added protection, wear a surgical mask.&nbsp; I usually work in front of a laminar flow hood, wear latex gloves and surgical mask(not dust mask) and a hair net.&nbsp; In addition, flame sterilize until red hot before each jar, and then let a drop or two of solution spill out to cool the needle slightly just before injecting while it's still hot.<br /><br />It's amazing how few contaminated syringes I buy when using that method. <img style=\"max-width:192px;height:auto;\" src=\"https://files.shroomery.org/smileys/grin.gif\" alt=\":grin:\" title=\":grin:\"/><br />RR","title":"Re: slimy yellow stuff on grain","forum":"Mushroom Cultivation"}}